Given a type descriptor and a Church-encoded value,
return its recursive children as a Scott list
of Church values.
Constructors with no recursive fields return [].

A type descriptor is a Scott list of constructor specs.
Each spec is a Scott list of fields.
Each field (Œªx.x) marks a recursive position.
In Haskell notation:
  data Bit  = O | I             is [[],[]]
  data Nat  = Z | S Nat         is [[],[‚ä§]]
  data Bin  = E | O Bin | I Bin is [[],[‚ä§],[‚ä§]]
  data Pair = A | B Pair Pair   is [[],[‚ä§,‚ä§]]
Nat encodes as:
  Œªc.Œªn.c(Œªc.Œªn.n,
    Œªc.Œªn.c(Œªc.Œªn.c(Œªx.x, Œªc.Œªn.n),
    Œªc.Œªn.n))

A Church value folds recursive fields by applying
them to all case-handlers:
  Nat Z:       Œªz.Œªs.z
  Nat S(S(Z)): Œªz.Œªs.s(s(z))

A Scott list: Nil = Œªc.Œªn.n, Cons(h,t) = Œªc.Œªn.c(h,t).

